{
  "doc_id": "42082",
  "text": "Isolates from both Clade A and Clade C lack φSE20, which is a 41 kb phage related to φST64B from S. Typhimurium [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . φSE20 is intact in the P125109-like Clade B isolates and in P125109 where it is thought to be a recent acquisition and has been implicated in S. Enteritidis virulence in mice and the invasion of chicken ova [CITATION_3] . Betancor et al., have suggested that the presence of φSE20 in S. Enteritidis is associated with the emergence of particular isolates as epidemic strains in Uruguay as they have found that 3 out of 6 pre-epidemic isolates lacked φSE20 while only 5 out of 108 epidemic and post-epidemic isolates lacked φSE20 [CITATION_4] . Similarly, φSE20 was absent in isolates from the 1940s and 1950s tested by Porwollik et al., but was present in the more recent isolates [CITATION_5] . As mentioned above, Clade B LK5-like isolates do not contain φSE20 but do possess a Fels2-like prophage called RE-2010 .",
